      <p>Thousands of dogs and puppies find themselves suffering in shelters across the country each day… in desperate need of medical attention due to injury, disease and other life-threatening conditions.  You may know, OPH is committed to saving as many dogs as possible from becoming a “high kill shelter” statistic.  What you may not know is that OPH rescues dogs that are passed over because they have diseases such as Parvovirus, Heartworm, or other difficult to treat health conditions such as hip dysplasia, injured eyes or legs, and other treatable but expensive issues.  These dogs deserve a chance at a happy, healthy life, just as much as their healthy counterparts do.  Because of this core value: to never turn a dog away that we’ve committed to save—a great deal of resources can be required to save a sick dog.  To ensure we can always stand by these little souls, we ask that you consider a donation to the Little Miracle Fund. </p>

      <p>Meet Milagro (which means “miracle” in Spanish)... an OPH dog whose life is nothing short of a miracle.</p>

      <p>Milagro (or Milo for short) was part of a litter of puppies OPH accepted that had contracted Parvovirus (“Parvo”).  This disease is highly contagious and can spread rapidly in overcrowded shelters.  It is especially severe in puppies that are not protected by vaccination or maternal antibodies.  Vaccines can prevent Parvo, but mortality can reach 91% in untreated cases.  Puppies can go from behaving like normal, healthy animals, to declining rapidly with severe vomiting, diarrhea, weight-loss, and dehydration.  Milo’s litter of six became a litter of two in a matter of hours of their arrival.  Milo and his littermate, Jazz, were the only two remaining.  Something heroic was needed to save these last two puppies.  Thanks to donations from our supporters, we were able to rush Milo and Jazz to the hospital and have emergency care administered.  Despite their best efforts, we were unable to take Jazz home and she passed over the Rainbow Bridge.  But to every story there is a silver lining.  Thanks to the blood transfusion Milo received, he was able to begin the long journey to recovery.  Now, Milo is an ambassador for life-saving blood donations that are vital to pet hospital’s and their procedures that save dogs like Milo.</p>

      <p>Milos’ story helps illustrate how crucial donations are to help the abandoned dogs and puppies we rescue.  Regardless of their medical needs, OPH does not turn away a dog in need merely because it’s sick.  Ignoring these dogs would be counter to our mission.  Please consider a donation to the Little Miracle Fund.  Your donation will enable OPH to continue our mission of saving more sweet little pups like Milo.</p>
