      <p>Heartworm disease is a death sentence for almost all of the dogs in the south who are diagnoses with the disease.  The disease is fatal for dogs if the condition is left untreated and for many dogs in the south – the condition goes undetected until it’s too late.  In the lucky chance that a dog ends up in a shelter and has a rescue organization take notice… the battle for the heartworm positive dogs is not necessarily done. </p>

      <h5>How we are Helping Dogs who have Suffered</h5>

      <p>It’s true ~ There are many adorable faces in the shelters that just beg to be taken him home!  Many times people fall in love with a dog who seems like a match!  Then, a staff member informs the rescue or adopter that your little friend is heartworm positive…  At this point, many people walk away.  Something snaps and that instant connection and excitement is overcome with doubt, fear, or an inability to help.  People get concerned about the cost, long term health effect or simply don’t know enough about the condition.  We at OPH do not turn our back on heartworm positive dogs.  We believe all dogs deserve a forever home, especially since heartworm is treatable and preventable.</p>

      <p>The disease starts with a simple mosquito biting an infected dog.  When the insect takes aim at an unprotected dog (a dog who has not received monthly preventative medication), the bite places baby heartworm eggs into that dog’s bloodstream.  Certain bacteria in the blood, feed the eggs that grow into larvae and eventually adult heartworms.  These squiggly creatures make the dog’s heart their home.  Without treatment, that adorable little guy you passed up at the shelter will die.</p>

      <p>We have rescued, treated and placed many heartworm positive dogs with the help of our incredible team of supporters.  Without the commitment from caring veterinarians that work with us and provide treatment at a reduced rate, we could never save so many infected dogs.  But that is simply not enough.  Our adoption fees cannot cover the cost of heartworm treatment, so we rely on the generosity of our supporters to help save these deserving dogs.  OPH always has several heartworm positive dogs waiting for treatment before they can find their homes.  These furry friends need and deserve a home just as much as the other dogs.   Please consider a donation to our Have a Heart Fund to support OPH’s work to save heartworm positive dogs and to provide them with a second chance.</p>
